I’m about a week late for a 2022 recap. I wasn’t going to do one but then I thought about it, and it’s my page. Ima do what I want.

2022 was really challenging & lonely on some days, and light and exciting on others. It’s hard to sum anything up in 10 photos. But- because I am practicing the art of reflection instead of rushing to the next thing... Here we go:

1) I officially became bicoastal in January of last year. My LA apartment is v cute thanks to @aunt_viv. My goal is to spend 80% of the year out here. GIF: @kayemccoy_ 

2) I covered my first awards season carpet for @essence. The SAG Awards showed me there are levels to this red carpet life. LEVELS.

3) thanks to my fam at @amazonmusic @rotation, I saw my myself on a billboard in Times Square. My brother came with me! And If you haven’t, check out my station- R&B rotation in DJ MODE! Photo: @__gavo 

4) @morethanthatshow got a 2nd season and a best podcast of the year award from @adweek. Thanks to the Urban One PR team- I finally got on @breakfastclubam before @angelayee announced her show! A moment I’ll never forget. Also, MTT is coming back for s3! 👏🏾 photo; @dp.jolly 

5) I was on the @todayshow six times, in studio! 😭

6) finally got to co-host @broccolicity. Being home on that stage was a bucket list moment

7) hosted @whenweallvote’s inaugural summit! 

8) … And @michelleobama watched the livestream, said I was killing it and that she was proud of me! Life MADE. 🥲

9) bravo con was IT. Photo: @samvibes 

10) @ebonymagazine put me on their Power 100 in Media Mavens category. I’m still floating from that night. Photo: @befiercebefab 

This is a highlight reel. I also want you to know that I got a lot of “No’s,” heartbreaking news, had trouble losing my pandemic weight, fought off depression— AND had friends pass away this year. It wasn’t easy.

There’s always bad with the good. And vice versa. I think recaps are important because it reminds us that in all things, we can trust ourselves to find a way to make it through. My way is faith, so thank you God for keeping me and mine through another year—  especially in times like this.

2022, thank you. 2023, we here. I welcome all that you will bring.

Mamba, forever. We miss you, Kobe.

Thank you to Salt N Pepa for showing us how to show up as our full authentic, talented selves since hip hop took off. Legends, icons, and some of the dopest women I’ve had the pleasure of meeting. Thank you to @heatherlowery for having me!

As we celebrate Black History and Hip hop 50- thank you to Salt n Pepa, Rapsody, Baby Tate and all the women who take up space in music. I’m a fan of each of them. Rapsody and Tate are just as dope off the mic as they are when they are making powerful songs that remind us of who we are. 

As we enter into a new week- I hope all the women who get on the mic to host, report, create, or lead boardrooms, ministries, classrooms, and mold families never ever forget the power we yield when we use our voice. Let’s go. 🗣️❤️

There are so many blessings on my timeline. So many of us living our dreams and prayers, accomplishing what we worked for and showing up despite the obstacles we have to face each day. There are so many of us using our platforms for good— honoring others, reclaiming narratives, cheering loudly and speaking life and light where darkness tries its’ best to prevail.

I see you. I see us. And for all of it— God, thank you.

Thank you for the ways you are using your vessels for good.
Thank you for the ways you keep giving us what we need to be all you’ve called us to be.
Thank you for those of us who are still here trying to figure it all out- because we are here, in this time, on purpose. And we know You will give us wisdom and clarity.

As for me, thank you for the ways you are removing self-doubt and anxiety in this season so I can show up as myself. Imperfect, but fully present. Figuring it out by putting one foot in front of the other. Leaning on You for strength to carry it all— and experiencing how you never leave me alone as I seek You. Our relationship is the one I start and end my day with- so just wanted to give you the praise. 

To Him who is able to do exceedingly and abundantly more than we can ask, think or imagine…
Thank you for giving us what we need to carry it when you begin to do so. Thank you. Thank you. Thank you.

Amen. 🙏🏾🙏🏾🙏🏾

HBCU’s don’t just educate the next generation of students, they also provide a safe haven for higher learning for the children in the communities they inhabit. If you’ve been following me for a while, you know I grew up as a Howard baby— thanks to my mom. 

As a little girl, I took every pre-college course, art camp offering and activity they had because my mom loved her school so much. And still does as a member of the faculty. Watching the beauty, brilliance, and all around swag of the young women of HU influenced how I would eventually take up my own space as a Black girl in this world. 

HBCUs greatly impact their communities. And the little girl who watched the HU girls represent excellence personified… Grew up to find her own ways to be excellent, too. The same Yard my mom dragged me to as a baby ended up being the space of one of my favorite hosting gigs of all time. And that’s why I’m so excited to partner with @homedepot depot again for their @retoolyourschool program. Head to RetoolYourSchool.com to vote for your fave HBCU to get funding for campus improvements, community resources, student life and more. Voting is still happening now! Don’t miss it.

Reading this profile @originalmiadiamond wrote on my career brought me to tears. Not only because she is so talented, but also because it forced me to reflect in ways I haven’t had the time to in a while.

When you’re not exactly where you *want* to be (but always where you need to be- hello?!), it can be easy to forget how far you’ve come. I’ve been doing this journalism and hosting thing for years. As an intern prepping radio and tv studios, as a writer just trying to get my bylines out there, as a red carpet reporter, as a host in arenas, sharing my truths on podcasts, and as a TV show host… I’ve done A LOT and I still know people who *don’t* believe in me or my talent. And to be honest, it can get HARD.

I can’t even tell y’all the amounts of times this my confidence has been shattered or how many times I’ve mapped out plan B because things always seem so close- but so far. Thankfully, my parents raised me up to believe in a higher power and to follow the call God placed on my life- no matter what. 

It’s all working for my good because I am called to be here. I belong here. And I finally get that. From the time my dad said I’d be a “broadcast journalist” when I was two months old, this plan has been unfolding exactly how God has wanted it to. I’ve learned to radically trust in Him and his plans more than any noise that tries to distract me.

So, as I wait and work in faith for a permanent prime time and/or network hosting gig, an agent who believes in me and can put my names in rooms that can make that happen, take acting classes again and continue to show up for whatever God calls me to in the meantime— i have to stop and say thank you to God for keeping me in this Thang so far.

I’m thankful for every yes and every no. For every co-host I’ve had. Every person who did give me a chance. Every person who roots for me and says my names in rooms, and every friend/family who has prayed for and with me.

And lastly, I am thankful in advance for the big blessings that are coming because if there’s one thing I know- God’s going to keep showing out.

See y’all on primetime 🙋🏾‍♀️🗣️🗣️🗣️

Q1 had me on the brink of burnout, y’all. It’s glorious to hustle, but it’s even more glorious to relax. 

So last week, I shut everything down and finally did. 

At my favorite place in the world. 
Where God’s designs are uninterrupted. 
Where the sounds of the waves slow down time.
Where the blues of the oceans melt into the blues of the skies. Where I can hear myself think. Where my family has gone to escape the noise for over two decades. Where I smile deeply to myself and mean it. Where I reconnect to God, light and joy in peace.

We would film solo interviews, round table interviews, branded hits, have VO sessions, styling and hair, production meetings, and travel to locations on any given day. “WHAT IF YOUR LIFE DEPENDS ON YOU DOING WHAT GOD CALLED YOU TO DO?” 😭

This question sat on my spirit yesterday after @devonfranklin preached such an incredible word at @one.online. I had always planned to drop the promo for @healedgirlerapod yesterday, but when I was on the way to the 9a service, I asked God for a word to help me focus and not give in to anxiety.

And whew. God is alwayssss on time.

I am not a healing expert or a therapist. I have never been consistent as a content creator. I am funding this myself (for now, it won’t always be that way). And if I’m being honest, I’m scared about living in the space of vulnerability it takes to really put myself out there. I’m also scared no one will watch and it won’t impact people. 

But when I get out of feelings and in to my faith, I know that I know that I know I’m following pre-planned, divinely ordered steps from a God who wouldn’t play me. 

I know that I’ve put in a decade of work as a journalist, host and content creator and podcaster, and I have the skills I need to accomplish it. I know that dreams and ideas are downloaded into us on purpose. So here I am. Giving myself permission to not just try, but to do. 

Yep, doubt will creep in and outcomes will happen that I don’t love. I will mess up and say the wrong thing sometimes. I know I won’t be perfect. But- I know that God’s Will is. I’m taking a step towards God, even though my ankles are shaking. I’m keeping Jeremiah 29:11 at the tip of my tongue and moving forward.

Shout out to the creatives who pray, take steps, and figure it along the way. I’m so proud of us for saying “Yes” to whatever God is calling us to do. Let’s. Go. 🙏🏾

Thank you God in advance for whatever you will do with this project, and for using Devon for that powerful word.
